1 NAME John /Mitropolous/
2 GIVN John
2 SURN Mitropolous
2 _MARNM James
1 SEX M
1 BIRT
2 DATE 23 FEB 1890
2 PLAC Kacourica, Yortinias, Greece
1 DEAT Y
2 DATE 11 JUL 1976
2 PLAC Broward, Florida, USA
1 OCCU Restaurant Owner
1 NOTE Bio notes: He was born John Mitropolous, in the Community of Kakourekia, Greece, son of Dimitrios and Sophia (Gianoukos), and is enrolled in the archives of mail births in Archive No. 2 with a year of birth 1894.  He probably immigrated to this country in the early 20th Century (probably 1906-08).  He arrived in New York and lived with his cousins-in-law in Hartford, Ct.  where he worked at various jobs...mostly in the food business with his cousins.  His dream was to come to this country, work hard and make a new life filled with the opportunities he heard about while a boy in the Peloponises (sp.) Mountains, Greece.  He saved his money and opened a restaurant of his own in Hartford and sent for his brother, Nicholas, who left his wife and family in Greece.  As times were tough, he needed the money.  He did not have the dedication to this country that my Dad had and he went back to Greece with a considerable amount of money.  Being adventurous Dad traveled to 21 states before he married my mother.  After I was born in 1931, my parents opened a restaurant - the St. James - on Euclid Avenue, Cleveland, OH.   I'm not sure about the restaurants he had or their names and dates; but I know he had one in Hartford, Kansas City, MO, and one in Phila. at 5th & Olney Avenue.  This is where he met my mother who came to the restaurant on a date.  He was smitten at once.  In about 1936-37, he opened a restaurant at 30th & Lancaster Avenue, Phila. with his partner Johnny Papas and together they operated the restaurant for about 30 years.  Dad and my mother retired to Fort Lauderdale, FL.  When the Ellis Island Foundation opened their Wall of Honor, I enrolled my Dad (John Mitropoulos).  My father was the most wonderful, caring, 
2 CONT gentleman I have ever met and I have met quite a few including your Father and my Husband. - Written by daughter, Loretta Brown
2 CONT 
2 CONT 
2 CONT 
2 CONT 
2 CONT Dad came over from Greece and landed in Kansas City, Missouri.  He met Jesse James' son there and like the name James and wanted something more American(?) and changed it from Mitropoulos to James.  Did he have a restaurant there?  
2 CONT 
2 CONT He came to Philadelphia and met Anna K. Fiko and married her,  I was born May 30, 1937 and raised at 236 Maypole Rd in Upper Darby and attended St. Alice grade school.  I then went to the archdiocesan high school, which was West Catholic High School at 49 & Chestnut in Philadelphia.  I was on the dean's list but I am especially proud on not being absent or late for 4 years.  I took the local PTC or now SEPTA bus every morning and afternoon. After high school I went to Villanova College (now university) and received a Bachelor of Arts degree.  I met Father Falvey at Villanova and he gave me a scholarship to Villanova's School of Library Science.  This degree was not accredited by the American Library Association; so, I went to Drexel Institute of Technology(now Drexel University) and received my Masters in Informnation Science in 1970.  I worked at Villanova's Library full time for one year and several years on a part-time basis to supplement my income.  I worked at ISI (Institute for Scientific Information at 4th and Chestnut Streets for several years and managed the Science Citation Index and had 40 people working for me.  I needed more money and then landed a job at a lucrative company called Wyeth Laboratories and the rest is history. - Writen by son, John James
2 CONT 
2 CONT 
2 CONT 
2 CONT 
2 CONT Hi Wil, Nice to hear from you and to know how interested you are in the Mitropoulos-James family.  You are correct Gianoukos was Sophia's maiden name.  My father did not seem to feel comfortable speaking about the past.  Perhaps it was WWII and the suffering the Greek people went through during those difficult war years.  As I understand it...Uncle Nicholas was the oldest child -- I think my father, John, was next -- and there were two sisters.  My Dad called one Carola.  There was another brother Athenasas (sp.) (Arthur) who was born after my Dad left Greece.  My father left his portion of whatever was coming to him from his parents to the brother he never knew.  My Father never dwelled in the past and perhaps it was because he missed them all.  Dad was all about his family here in the U.S. and his restaurant business.  He educated himself as best as he could by going to Night School (learning English and Accounting).  While he was living in Canton, Ohio, he was Treasurer of the Greek Orthodox Church.  While living in Kansas City, MO, his lawyer was Jesse James, Jr. - who was a lawyer and then a judge.  My father admired him with the exception of his drinking too much.  I think he saw what it was doing to him and for the rest of his life my father did not have more than an occasional drink. - Written by daughter, Loretta Brown
2 CONT 
2 CONT Left Patras, Greece, and took a boat called "Polonia" to New York, New York on April 17, 1913 and became a United States citizen on August 22, 1916 at Hartford, CT, USA.
